commit.message:
Explicitly pass -XCPP to hlint

This is necessary because haskell-ci now passes -XHaskell2010 to hlint, which
causes it to disable language extensions that aren't part of Haskell2010 (e.g.,
CPP). This has the unfortunate consequence of hlint failing to parse any
modules that use CPP. To work around this, we now pass -XCPP explicitly to
hlint. This is a bit unfortunate—see ndmitchell/hlint#1360—but this should
let the CI pass for now.

Adapt to (~) becoming a type operator

`(~)` now requires `TypeOperators` in GHC 9.4 (see
https://gitlab.haskell.org/ghc/ghc/-/wikis/migration/9.4?version_id=503a517b7238e8bac3dd588f32e234bf74b17097#-is-now-a-type-operator)
to build without warnings.
CI: Use hlint on GHC 9.0 job
Qualified imports for Data.Text, Data.List.NonEmpty, Data.Foldable

Regenerate CI-related YAML files

This commit was performed automatically by a script.
https://github.com/RyanGlScott/ci-maintenance

Text.Parser.Token: disable -Wincomplete-uni-patterns

It's unclear to me what the best way to fix the incomplete uni-pattern in this
module is, but until then, let's not pollute the build with this warning.

Placate hlint by defining `count` more sensibly

In fact, `count` in the same thing as `replicateM` on modern versions of
`base`, so we may as well take advantage of this.

Migrate from Travis CI to GitHub Actions

Travis CI recently announced
[changes to its pricing model](https://blog.travis-ci.com/2020-11-02-travis-ci-new-billing)
that will affect OSS projects. Whereas Travis previously allowed unrestricted
hours for OSS projects to run on their build machines, the new pricing model
will require the use of credits, of which free plans only have a limited
quantity. Moreover, Travis now takes an extraordinarily long time to actually
serve CI requests, which is infeasible in the long term.

As a result, I have decided
(with encouragement from other Haskell maintainers, see
[here](https://old.reddit.com/r/haskell/comments/jvbs49/psa_maintainers_should_think_about_migrating_off/))
to migrate to GitHub Actions. This
relies on a very recent version of `haskell-ci` that features a GitHub Actions
backend.

Depend on semigroups only on GHC < 8.0 (#82)

They are not needed on newer GHC.
